  "local_port": 41322,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some ideas for projects in data structures using C/C++?",
  "response": "Creating projects in data structures can help you understand core concepts and improve problem-solving skills. Here are some ideas for projects in C/C++:\n\n1. **Library Management System**:\n   - Implement a system to manage books in a library using data structures like hash tables, linked lists, and binary search trees.\n   - Features could include adding/removing books, searching for books by title or author, and tracking borrowed books.\n\n2. **Hospital Patient Management System**:\n   - Use queues and linked lists to manage patient records and appointment scheduling.\n   - Include functionalities for patient check-in, check-out, and priority handling based on medical conditions.\n\n3. **Student Record Management**:\n   - Utilize arrays, structures, and file handling to create a system that stores and retrieves student records.\n   - Implement searching and sorting algorithms to organize records efficiently.\n\n4. **Social Network Graph**:\n   - Build a social network model using graphs where nodes represent users and edges represent friendships.\n   - Implement functionalities like finding mutual friends, shortest path between users, and suggesting new friends.\n\n5. **Maze Solver Using Backtracking**:\n   - Implement a maze solving algorithm using stack or recursive data structures.\n   - Provide visualization of the solution path and different algorithms like DFS or BFS.\n\n6. **Text Editor**:\n   - Develop a basic text editor with functionalities like editing, saving, and opening files using linked lists for dynamic line management.\n   - Implement undo/redo functionality using stacks.\n\n7. **Priority Queue for Task Scheduling**:\n   - Create a scheduler that uses heaps to manage tasks based on priority.\n   - Allow dynamic adjustment of task priorities and automatic execution of highest priority tasks.\n\n8. **File System Simulation**:\n   - Simulate a simple file system using trees where each node represents a file or directory.\n   - Implement functionalities for adding/removing files, navigating directories, and searching for files.\n\n9. **Railway Reservation System**:\n   - Use linked lists and queues to manage reservation and cancellation of tickets.\n   - Implement search and sort functionalities for querying reservations.\n\n10. **Chat Application**:\n   - Develop a client-server chat application with functionalities like sending and receiving messages using socket programming.\n   - Use suitable data structures to manage active connections and message queues.\n\n11. **Dynamic Memory Management**:\n   - Create a memory allocator and deallocator simulating malloc/free using linked lists.\n   - Implement algorithms for best-fit, worst-fit, and first-fit memory allocation strategies.\n\n12. **Sales Analysis System**:\n   - Use hash maps to store sales data and linked lists to manage transactions.\n   - Implement querying functionalities to generate sales reports and statistics.\n\n13. **Expression Evaluator**:\n   - Implement an infix, postfix, and prefix expression evaluator using stacks.\n   - Handle operator precedence and parenthesis correctly.\n\n14. **Spell Checker**:\n   - Utilize trie or hash maps to implement a spell checker.\n   - Include functionalities for suggesting corrections based on dictionary entries.\n\nThese projects will give you practical experience with various data structures and algorithms, helping you strengthen your programming skills in C/C++. Consider starting with simpler projects and progressively tackling more complex ones as you build confidence and expertise.",
